NOTICE that control of the robot via FCl is not possible when the SLP-C, SLS-C or SLP-J functions are active.
This affects the safety functions that include spatial position monitoring (Inside/Outside Area) and Cartesian
velocity monitoring (maximum Velocity). If these are used in rules in Watchman, control via FCl is not possible.
Data is sent over the network with a frequency of 1 kHz.Therefore,a good network connection is required!
While the FCl is active you have full, exclusive control of the Arm and Franka Hand. This means that Arm
control cannot be performed via Apps and FCl at the same time!
13.7.1 Working in principle with the FCl interface
Controlling the robot via the FCl interface can be realized by using libfranka in the C++ environment. A sound
knowledge of Linux environment and C++ programming is recommended for this purpose.
Alternatively, the robot can be controlled via the FCl interface by ROS, ROS 2.
The following section describes the basic procedure for programming with the help of libfranka in the C++
environment.
Executables
Via the libfanka described before in chapter 13.7 "Franka Control Interface (FCl)" executable files (executables)
can be created.
In the "examples" subfolder of libfranka, examples of executables are listed. You can use these as a base to get
started easily and create copies from them that are customized according to your requirements.
Below you will find the source code of the example" generate_joint_position_motion.cpp" from libfranka to
explain the structure of a script.
